./review.md:263:- **[LOW]** `createJsonRpcFetcher` violates its exported response type — `packages/jsonrpc/src/createJsonRpcFetcher.js:24` _(from H08)_
./review.md:729:### [LOW] `createJsonRpcFetcher` violates its exported response type
./review.md:730:**Location:** packages/jsonrpc/src/createJsonRpcFetcher.js:24
./review.md:731:**Issue:** `createJsonRpcFetcher` is declared to return `JsonRpcClient`, whose `JsonRpcResponse` type requires a `method` field, but the runtime success and error responses omit `method`. The tests assert the method-less shape, so the type and runtime contract disagree.
./review.md:733:**Suggested fix:** Either remove `method` from `JsonRpcResponse` if the package intends to model standard JSON-RPC responses, or add `method: request.method` to every `createJsonRpcFetcher` response and keep the nonstandard Tevm response shape consistent.
./review.md:1209:**Issue:** `createJsonRpcFetcher` is included in a type-only export block from `@tevm/jsonrpc`, while the generated declaration file advertises it as a normal named export from `tevm` and the generated JS only exports `http`, `rateLimit`, `webSocket`, and `loadBalance` from `@tevm/jsonrpc`.
./review.md:1210:**Why it matters:** TypeScript consumers can write `import { createJsonRpcFetcher } from 'tevm'` without a type error, but the ESM/CJS runtime entrypoints do not actually provide that binding. This is a public barrel footgun that turns into an import-time failure for users following the published types.
./review.md:1211:**Suggested fix:** Either move `createJsonRpcFetcher` into the runtime export block next to `http`/`rateLimit`, or remove it from the top-level declarations if it is intentionally not part of the `tevm` barrel. Regenerate and verify `tevm/index.js`, `tevm/index.cjs`, and `tevm/index.d.ts` agree.
